  "doc_id": "34831",
  "text": "Pubertal status was assessed with the self-reported Petersen Physical Development Scale (PPDS) [CITATION_1] annually from ages 9-15 years. Previous studies show strong correlations between self-reported and physician ratings of pubertal status even in children under age 9 [CITATION_2] . The PPDS includes four questions about growth spurt, pubic and axillary hair, breast development, and changes in skin rated on a four-point scale (1 ¼ has not yet begun; 2 ¼ has barely started; 3 ¼ is definitely underway; 4 ¼ seems completed) and one yes/no question about menstruation onset. Summary scores of girls' pubertal maturation each year were calculated by averaging the five questions, where the menstruation item was recoded to 1 (has not started) and 4 (started). Though [CITATION_3] used measures of breast, hair growth, and menarche to classify girls by Crockett staging in the larger PGS study, the current method allowed us to capture multiple events of puberty associated with both gonadal and adrenal hormonal development on a continuous scale (1 ¼ minimum pubertal maturation; 4 ¼ maximum pubertal maturation), and has been used in previous studies [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
